subject: [SampleApps] User cannot access to HTTP server listened on the module
commitMessage:
[SampleApps] User cannot access to HTTP server listened on the module

Description:
    Regression issue because it did not happen on R17BP8 but R17BP9
Root cause:
    The toolchain of R17BP9 using the libprocps.so.8 but httpServer.adef with hardcode of libprocps.so.7
Solution:
    Use bundle section to get library from toolchain and remove version syntax in case of issue happening again

Resolves: LE-16376
Related: QTI9X07-5548
Change-Id: If52cb1dcc94ddeb470cd7565e68c2fe7070ef502
Signed-off-by: Philip Yeh <pyeh@sierrawireless.com>

Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as d56886de1e1657c414763e73348de6c78d7fd59d

Instead of hardcoding library versions, I prefer we just use the one from the toolchain we are building with. This will not break compatibility if users decide to use an older toolchain and load it on a newer linux that has .8 version.

You can reference: http://cgit-legato/Legato/tree/components/3rdParty/curl/Component.cdef as an example. Here you can see that instead of using the "requires" section and using the library from the target. We copy the library using the "bundle" section from the toolchain. We check what version is available and copy them over.

subject: Update atServer parsing rules for LGU commands
commitMessage:
Update atServer parsing rules for LGU commands

Particularly relax checking rules for LGU commands.
Not to abort LGU cmd when it's not encapsulate with quotes.

To prevent affecting those common commands and workflow of atServer,
these changes are built when LGTRASS command enabled (MK_CONFIG_AT_LGTRASS)
and recogninze LGU command with 'AT$LG' at runtime.

Resolves: LE-16609
Related: QTI9X07TX-3927
Change-Id: Id108496bab394bbb8a2794860c1868e44656767b

subject: Allow escaping ', " and \ within quoted strings
commitMessage:
Allow escaping ', " and \ within quoted strings

In quoted strings, make a backslash (\) escape single quote ('),
double quote (") and backslash (\) characters.

Testing this revealed a few other issues with escape character
handling which have been fixed with this patch:

 - Quote characters were not escaped when passed through the shell in
   cflags, cxxflags, and ldflags, resulting in these variables getting
   manged.  Add escaping to these.
 - EscapeQuotes only escaped double quotes.  Add the capability to also
   escape backslashes and single quotes to support the above.
 - EscapeQuotes would mangle string if there were more than one escaped
   character in the string due to passing the _position_ of the _end_ of
   the second string fragment to substr rather than the _length_ of the
   second and later string fragments.
 - tinydtls would remove quoting from CFLAGS and LDFLAGS when passing to
   configure, corrupting these variables; add escaping for double
   quotes. The solution is not general as it only covers double quotes,
   and only in tinydtls, but this was the only place the problem was
   observed in practice.

Resolves: LE-16583
Change-Id: I73670869737c2ba06c98356a6eb7e2816d1e02eb

subject: Fix stack overflow issue in secStore
commitMessage:
Fix stack overflow issue in secStore

After introducing of IKS, secStore thread in ThreadX requires more stack
memory. With current memory allocation secStore is corrupting thread
table and adjacent thread memory, hence device behave very unexpectedly
(frequent reboot, fota failure, crash during new thread spawn etc).
Increased secStore stack size, hence it can accomdate new IKS based key
read/write.

Resolves: LE-16536 QTI9X07TX-3843
Change-Id: I2246bece4731ab816e6e388dac046ea852f0066f

subject: Refactor thread destruction logic
commitMessage:
Refactor thread destruction logic

This patch refactors the thread object destruction logic to always
maintain a reference in the thread which is destroyed when the thread
exits.  Then if the thread is joinable, also add a reference which
is released when the thread is joined.

This change should have no effect in general, but works around some
RTOS platforms with non-existant or broken join logic.

Resolves: LE-16545
Change-Id: Ifd2c9f692b4f4fe0d20e40af9cb0afbe4c5678df

Is there any defined macro for it like the rest of cases here?

POSIX specifies:

> RETURN VALUE
> 
>     If successful, the pthread_join() function shall return zero; otherwise, an error number shall be returned to indicate the error.

So checking against 0 for success is appropriate here.  Even if there is a macro on some platforms, it would be non-portable.

subject: Zero memory block when releasing
commitMessage:
Zero memory block when releasing

Zero memory blocks when releasing them.  This reduces chance of
data leak into subsequent user, and improves compression for systems
which hibernate.

Resolves: LE-16523

subject: Ignore format-truncation in some unit tests
commitMessage:
Ignore format-truncation in some unit tests

Some versions of GCC report a format truncation warning in AT unit
tests.  These are unit tests, and the test works correctly since
all inputs are much less than the maximum size, so these warnings
can safely be ignored for these tests.

Resolves: LE-16523
Change-Id: I19590548e261e38af53b4bb736a72f0447bb1711

subject: Add environment initialization for LeTP container
commitMessage:
Add environment initialization for LeTP container

Install the necessary packages for "make localhost" and set the
$LEGATO_ROOT.

With the Python 2 dependencies dropped, ifgen and other tools can just
use installed Python 3 Pip packages.

Resolves: LE-16477
Change-Id: Ia55479516dbdc2689f93867ddfdb89e7bc80c06e

subject: Fix FTPS send and receive
commitMessage:
Fix FTPS send and receive

Based on RFC4217 section 12.7, when a client attempts to send or receive
data in passive mode, using TLS security, it must send the STOR or RETR
command prior to attempting to open the data channel.

Resolves: ATSWI-283
Change-Id: Ic76d719f2d2dcdb7c8d845e0e3b73259be54f1d6

subject: Fix race condition in FTP client library.
commitMessage:
Fix race condition in FTP client library.

Prior to this patch, when we initiate a passive FTP data retrieve, the
FTP client would first issue a RETR (retrieve) command and then connect
to the FTP server's data port. When executing the happy path, where the
file path parameter RETR exists on the remote, the implementation is OK.
Problems arise when the file path is non-existent; the server may close
the data port upon receipt of the invalid path BEFORE the client has a
change to attempt a TCP connection to it. This race condition manifests
itself as unpredictable error codes being received on the client side:

 - 90% of the time the FTP server tested against
(ftp5.sierrawireless.com) would close the data socket before the client
connect()'s to it resulting in a TCP connection reset error
 - 10% of the time FTP client connect()'s to the server's data port
before the server has a change to reset the connection and as a result
the client gets back the FTP 550 (file not found) error code - this is
the expected behaviour

This patch reverses the order of the operations such that the FTP client
always first connects to the FTP server's data port BEFORE it issues the
FTP retrieve request.

This patch also adds several log messages to netSocket_Connect in order
to more easily diagnose connection failures in the future.

Resolves: ATSWI-235
Change-Id: I2727d37648e096d5f4cf70a9e0ff27298cd7dc03

subject: Fix AllowCommunications inside serviceDirectory
commitMessage:
Fix AllowCommunications inside serviceDirectory

Currently, this function is attempting to give socket's input and
output labels that will allow communications between two processes
however given that the serviceDirectory is only a framework label,
therefore it won't have such privilleges. Furthermore, this function
doesn't return anything when it fails.

Now, we will check if the labels are correct first, such that
IPIN socket label can write to the server's process label.
Similarily between server process label writing to IPOUT. Also
changed AllowCommunication to only check if the client process'
socket is allowed to sent to the server rather than any type
of setting of socket labels. Furthermore, also changed the
serviceDirectory label to "serviceDirectory" which is a label
that has all prvileges of "framework" but with the ability to
"rx" on "admin" thus allowing it to read all process labels.

Resolves: LE-15818
Change-Id: I9d10ca6716336d14cbe4c4f2dd7630bfdd8a0bd7

There is now a comprehensive fix for socket labels in https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/+/78375
Currently, there are two patches, the patch #1's commit message and comments and in JIRA also has the reasoning for why I've uploaded patch #2

I feel that this change would get us further from the desired solution, rather than closer. I looked into SMACK kernel code and found some things:
(1) SMACK credentials for unix domain sockets are checked only during connection establishment, at which point the SMACK64IPIN and SMACK64IPOUT labels are checked against access rules.
(2) After the connection is established, unix domain sockets are free to communicate without checking labels.
(3) The exception to above rule is if control information is attached to the message, in which case smack_file_receive() checks sender and receiver SMACK64 labels.
I suspect we are using SO_PASSSEC on unix stream sockets, which attaches control information. If we don't use SO_PASSSEC on stream sockets, then only (1) and (2) would apply. In that case we can create a "supervisor-connect" label for supervisor socket and allow write access to that label for anyone that needs to talk to supervisor. This is much more stringent that giving write access to "admin" which could in theory overwrite the supervisor executable.

Hi Zoran,

First off, thanks for the in depth analysis!

Quick update: 

Yeah, we are using control messages to pass lots of data such as FD(SCM_RIGHTS) and credentials(SCM_CREDENTIALS) via unixSocket_SendMsg. This is the method that the service directory is using to pass client FD's to the server. Regarding SO_PASSSEC, it seems like it's another part of the control messages under SCM_SECURITY

Looking at 3) I wanted to see if remove SO_PASSEC will make the connection establishment fail. Therefore, I removed setsockopt for SO_PASSSEC and it also returns the same issue at the same place when the server attempts to retrieve the FD. Therefore, this makes me believe there is something else. I'll continue to look into this and see.

I think the reason for why it isn't failing at the connection point is because how this connection is established. Here the client and server both connect to the serviceDirectory, via different pathnames. It's the serviceDirectory which then sends messages between client and server rather than a direct connection between the two processes. Therefore, there needs to be some sort of control on the serviceDirectory before it begins sending these control messages.

We have a document on Confluence, describing the generic SMACK/Onlycap design - in particular what labels are available and how are they assigned. 
Now if we are introducing a new label here, the document needs to be updated - otherwise it will become even more out-of-date.

I agree with this comment. With the onlycap changes on 4.14, it's hard to understand all the rules for the system and whether the system is secure. Can we put something together and review that first? Thx!

subject: Fix compilation error when LE_CONFIG_SOTA is removed
commitMessage:
Fix compilation error when LE_CONFIG_SOTA is removed

When LE_CONFIG_SOTA is disabled, the linux build cannot be compiled. There should be no dependency between LE_CONFIG_SOTA and LE_CONFIG_PROBATION_PERIOD. In addition, this patch also fixes the AVC connection when LE_CONFIG_SOTA is removed. The secure storage path construction should not be affected by LE_CONFIG_SOTA.

Resolves: LE-16444
Change-Id: I4f27c5cf83309f5a7bfc1881355d9a36f2cb64c4

Hi Keith,
    Thanks for your code sharing, as my testing after sending abort cmd the flow will fall into FTP_XFERING->FTP_CLOSING state("fail case" due to not handling resp code), the ftp client session will be closed. 
    If wanna handle resp code of "ABOR", Different FTP server will response different code so can't handle it by resp code.
    I add some code based on yours to let the ftp client session alive matched to KFTPSND, please help to review it [80095 #1]

ABOR FTP command
The ABOR command can be issued by the client to abort the previous FTP command. If the previous FTP command is still in progress or has already completed, the server will terminate its execution and close any associated data connection. This command does not cause the connection to close.

Hi Philip:

Thanks for the catch on ftp session being closed due to not being a recognized response code.  But I think there needs to be some code to handle the response code to the ABOR command or we can end up in a bad state -- at least read.  I suggest recognizing 426 response code since this is the "correct" transfer aborted code; if another code is received we can follow the unknown error path and close the connection.  What do you think?

According this modification my ftp server A response 426 code will ok to abort and ftp client connection is alive.

My ftp server B which will response 550 code will fall into 'fail case' and close ftp client connection (this I think is ok to tell customer that ftp server return wrong resp code)

Hi Philip:

On my test server sending ABOR will cause the server to close the data connection, in which case FtpClientDataHandler will be triggered with le_socket_Read returning 0 (end of file), triggering transfer_end.  Does this not happen in your case?

Thanks,
-- Keith

Hi Philip:

If possible I'd prefer to keep the logic I have currently as it is the same logic as is used for regular end of transfer, so has already been tested and debugged in that context.

Given this is needed imminently for R9BP8 I am going to merge as-is, and we can change in a new patch if needed.

Thanks,
-- Keith

Hi Keith,
    You can verify this MOL ticket ftp site as my testing the current code will not return back to command mode

    AT+KFTPCFG=1,"116.66.221.43","swae","swappeng",21,1
    AT+KFTPRCV=1,,,"Big_dummy.txt",0

Thanks,
Philip

subject: Define le_avc API for setting LwM2M credentials.
commitMessage:
Define le_avc API for setting LwM2M credentials.

This patch adds a new API to le_avc that is used to provision LwM2M
credentials on the device. The current use case is atAirVantage's +WAMS
command handler can pass a LwM2M credential - configured by the factory
- to AVC, which uses it to connect to AVMS.

Resolves: LE-16440
Change-Id: I16eebb9b13f22f0fe2eaf9f609f2332f04d6a6f9

subject: Return ERROR when connecting MQTT broker with wrong password
commitMessage:
Return ERROR when connecting MQTT broker with wrong password

When connecting to broker using wrong passsword, the embedded paho
lib (specifically the function MQTTConnect()) will return result
code 5, which is decoded from a socket packet when expecting for
CONNACK and not handled by le_mqttClientLib. This leads to
incorrectly converting the result code to a LE_OK to KMQTT and
hence no ERROR is output. Thus, enhancing the result code
conversion logic fixes this issue.

Resolves: LE-16322
Change-Id: I931ff95a48edf8cfa5f6b8a0dfa6f56a2c97d272

subject: Fix app's RW bundle file missing issue
commitMessage:
Fix app's RW bundle file missing issue

Legato can't recover app's RW bundled files when legato RW partition
(/mnt/flash/legato) is reformatted. Linux init script formats
/mnt/flash/ partition if it is get corrupted or erased. However,
legato recovery mechanism assumes there should be always something
in /mnt/flash/legato directory, hence, it fails to recover app RW
bundled files when /mnt/flash partition is reformatted. This patch
fixes legato recovery mechanism when /mnt/flash partition is
reformatted.

Resolves: LE-16369
Related: MOLWP9X07-1027
Change-Id: I4db7a0c93dbd4cb5dd7b58b94a2f49613da12e86

Hi all,

Shall we remove the QCA section, considering it is concerning Yocto build and not Legato build?

Regards
Anju
Should use the word "device" or "module" instead. "Application processor" is only one processors on the module and the firmware releases include a binary that updates several procs.
Modem update requires re-certification. Can we check with WP team whether the modem really gets updated in these releases?

This is not really a "use case". It belongs to something like a "caveat" section in which we describe what changes are required to customer code prior to being installed with this release, or what actions need to be taken after installing.
This belongs to BSP documentation. WP release notes may be a better home for it.
This belongs to the "caveat" section. See my comment below about updating keys in IoT keystore.
I think this should not be present in a Legato documentation. This belongs to Yocto documentation. Probably, in the WP release notes.
I agree with Anju's comment. This belongs to WP release notes.
This goes into something like "new features" section. But didn't we say that we would hold off on IoT keystore support until next release to avoid two-stage update?
Can someone please let me know if this is to be removed, or added to a "New Features" section.

Let's remove it for now. There's two issues mentioning it right now
1) Features has not been fully tested on WP77
2) Product team hasnt decided if they want this feature in the upcoming release yet.
Thanks!

Some of the topics defined as "use cases" are warnings to customer what changes need to be made to their code to run with this version of firmware. I proposed calling this a "caveat" section, but a doc writer might pick a better term for it.

Topic on WiFi and Bluetooth should be moved to WP release notes.

We also need to understand to what extent we want to disclose IoT keystore feature. At some point we decided to hold it off for another release to avoid two-stage FOTA update.

Seems like document mentions release 20.03 instead of 20.05.

Does this need to cherry-picked to 21.05-release branch?

21.05-release branch currently has the followings:

alng@alng-All-Series:~/legato_21.05-release/legato$ find . -name getStarted.dox
./framework/doc/getStarted.dox

alng@alng-All-Series:~/legato_21.05-release/legato$ find . -name buildAppsMain.dox
./framework/doc/buildAppsMain.dox

alng@alng-All-Series:~/legato_21.05-release/legato$ find . -name howToMain.dox
./framework/doc/howToMain.dox

and this is a new file added:
legatoMigrationGuide.dox
Yes it does, I can cherry-pick it but i'll do it once we get a +2 on this patch.
Still some questions need to be answered.
I am assuming you mean 21.03/21.05.  I have replaced all references to 21.03 with 21.05

If we are gonna mention 21.05.0, we should have have another row:

4.14    3.1    LXSWI3.1-2.0    21.05.0

Apologize for missing this before but I think we should not use alex machine as the example. Can you we make up a username like 'user@legato' instead of alng@alng-All-Series. Also let's modify the ip from 192.168.3.2 to 192.168.2.2 as this is the default one.
Good point. Beware that other than alng@alng-All-Series, also change all instances of path /home/alng to /home/user

subject: Add a check for valid fdMonitor reference before enabling it
commitMessage:
Add a check for valid fdMonitor reference before enabling it

In same cases such as MQTT broker turns off the service before
client ends first, a POLLRDHUP will trigger the fdMoniter in
le_socketLib to delete and reset to NULL, but if client tries to
read again, le_socketLib will try to enable the fdMonitor again
which is no longer valid. Adding a check before enabling it fixes
an assertion exit.

This patch also

1. Optimizes the event handler of le_mqttClientLib to not
   continuously read from network when a POLLRDHUP is received.

2. Fixes an issue when TCP connection is successful but MQTT
   connection is not (e.g., connecting to a TCP only server), some
   clean up was not done. So, adding le_mqttClient_StopSession()
   when MQTTConnect() failed.

Resolves: LE-16434
Change-Id: I1eddf4868cd1c13607844b321da98f4ecbb21d58

subject: Extend Legato MQTT AT service to support AWS MQTT
commitMessage:
Extend Legato MQTT AT service to support AWS MQTT

These changes modify the AT+KMQTTCFG AT Command, as follows:

1. Add a new optional field, <cipher_index>, to the end of the AT+KMQTTCFG command
to allow users to specify a cipher suite profile index, defined by +KSSLCRYPTO,
which will be used when establishing secured MQTT connections.
This field would be mandatory for all secure MQTT connections
(i.e. <secure> setting equals 1).  The cipher suite configuration profile,
among other things, allows users to enable Mutual-Authentication
when configuring secure socket connections.

2. Add a new optional field, <ALPN Protocol Name>,
at the end of the AT command.

In addition, these changes extend the le_socket library to
support the configuring of the ALPN protocol list, as well as,
extend the MQTT Client library and adaptor to support Mutual-
Authentication.

Resolves: ATSWI-273
Change-Id: Ifb5ed0352c4725834c7fb73ff18310664457158a

subject: Disable FTPS client functionality
commitMessage:
Disable FTPS client functionality

Disables secure FTP for builds that do not support it by stubbing out
the TLS session negotiation functions by having them return
LE_NOT_IMPLEMENTED.

Resolves: ATSWI-278
Change-Id: I2785d456be694207248bd91963166440686d107d

subject: Fix NULL parameter passed to API response function
commitMessage:
Fix NULL parameter passed to API response function

The generated code asserts that the "name" parameter is not NULL, so
initialize it to an empty string, even if the function is returning an
error.  Additionally, use the buffer size rather than the string length
during string comparison when searching the AT command registry.

Resolves: LE-16402
Change-Id: Iba61f02897c1d5fb06b496f98cf6a88a35e65a5e

Patch Set 7:

Sarah, I think we should try to modify the section of the API documentation that describes the API syntax,

https://docs.legato.io/latest/apiFilesSyntax.html

In particular, the section describing the string IN and string OUT.

==========================================================================

"string" <name> "[" <maxSize> "]" "IN" 

    an IN string
    maxSize specifies the maximum string length allowed,
    string length is given as number of characters, excluding any terminating characters

Deprecated:
    [ <minSize> ".." ] is now deprecated. Only <maxSize> needs to be specified.

"string" <name> "[" <maxSize> "]" "OUT" 

    an OUT string
    string should be large enough to store maxSize characters; if supported by the function implementation, a shorter OUT string can be used.
    string length is given as number of characters, excluding any terminating characters

<handlerType> <name> 

    a handler (callback) function.
    see apiFilesSyntax_handler for info on how to declare a handler.

The returnType is optional, and if specified, can be any type that's not an array, string, or handler.

Warning
    Make sure that the function's maxSize is appropriately defined. If the client sends a value that larger then the <maxSize>, an error will be written to the log ((strlen(<name>) | <name>Size) > <maxSize>) and the client will be terminated.

============================================================================



Suggestions:
1. Move "Warning" to string IN case, as this is where it applied.
2. Re-write string OUT case to better reflect that for langC the string buffer should be maxSize+1, in order to hold the string + null-terminator.

Patch Set 5:

Alex, some notes to be discussed when you are back.

Regarding the "=" in FindAncestorSys, I have been operating under the assumption that the "=" isn't there.  
In the case of system rollback, FindAncestorSys wouldn't have been called because there's a check to see if current system index is already in SecStoreSystems list.

There are two things I didn't consider in the current design:
1. A system without secstore could be installed.
2. Currently further changes to a probational system would increment its system index.

So we need to be able to identify which system in the SecStoreSystems list is the "last good" system by either:
1. Marking "good" or "probational" on systems on the secstore side.
2. Assume that the older of the 2 systems must be good, since right now at any point in time there is either only 1 system (good), or 2 systems (good and probational).

With either approach, when the Legato probational system turns good, secstore daemon needs to be notified and update right away. Cannot wait until the next Legato start anymore.

Also, if the user turns off secstore daemon on a system that's meant to have it, we can't guarantee things would work properly. For example, if secstore daemon is turned off so that it doesn't get the notification that Legato probational system has turned good.
Shouldn't leak this type of design info.
Could use a flag so that the list is not searched multiple times.

SyncSystems does a check at the beginning so that if there are no changes to the Legato system, the syncing (and all subsequent list building and searching etc.) are skipped.  Therefore the list isn't searched unnecessarily.  I assume you are referring to the case when read/write/delete are performed on a "good" system.
I'm not sure I understand the need for this.  If the ancestor system is always going to be good, no?

The purpose is to keep the index number up-to-date, so to make debugging with the secStore tool less confusing.  Otherwise the last good system index number on the Legato side is going to be different from that on the secStore side.

It's one extra copy, but underneath we are just creating links so the performance hit and space consumption aren't that bad.
As discussed this can lead to data loss with the current implementation of system rollback.

Done... and I have also changed the variable naming from "ancestor" to "lastGood" or "lastKnownGood" to make the current model clearer.  I am keeping the naming of "FindAncestorSys" function because the definition of "ancestor", as defined in the function header, still holds true.  If you really want to get rid of "ancestor", I guess I can change it to "prev" or "previous".
It would be helpful to document the overall design here.
Should be less than or equal to.
TBD: This way of finding the "last known good" system in SecStoreSystems is wrong. If there are two existing ancestor systems, then the older one is the good one.

Under what situations can we have a secureCtxPtr without isSecure being set?  I'd add a comment to the code explaining this.
Agree, or this block might be moved into the above if.

The secureCtxPtr is initialized whenever a certificate, private key, cipher suite, etc. are configured, which is independent of whether the socket connection was secure or not.  That's why it needs to be checked by itself, outside of contextPtr->isSecure check.

I will add a comment, as suggested.
Can you maybe elaborate on this?  Sounds counter-intuitive -- I would think a socket would only have a secure context if it was secure.

The real problem is that the context->isSecure boolean, which is checked in the le_socket_Delete(), is only set to true when a secure connection has been successfully established.  So, if we attempted to establish a secure connection but it fails, this flag will be set to false.  This resulted in a memory leak when the secure connection failed.

Additionally, there is also a use-case where the Cipher Suite is set, but without a Certificate or Private Key.   This will cause the secure context pointer to be initialized, but will not trigger a secure connection.   Again, leading to a memory leak on the socket deletion.

This is why I separated the connection method (secure vs. non-secure) from the releasing of the secure context. The safest way to know whether we need free/release the secure context pointer via secSocket_Delete() is to check if it has been set or not.

I think it would be clearer to mention these cases, rather than saying the two are independent.  Because they're not independent -- rather secureContext may be created because the user is starting to establish a secure connection, but isSecure is not yet set because a secure connection has not yet been established.
Although, I think the secure flag and the secure connection related resource shall be bound, might be a further improvement.
They used to be -- but they had to be (partially) separated to fix a bug.

subject: Check if device is in data mode at the right place
commitMessage:
Check if device is in data mode at the right place

Previously le_port_SetDataMode() does not return LE_DUPLICATE because it
did not check whether the device is already in the Data Mode at the
right place: it checked if we could disable fdMonitor for the device,
which should never fail.

Since we store the Data Mode file descriptor in the context variable, by
checking if the device has a valid Data Mode file descriptor, we can
accurately determine if the device is under the Data Mode.

Resolves: LE-13923
Change-Id: Id17b1d600bc63938a565b58373f5b1d2795691d5

subject: Correct errno check on strtol call
commitMessage:
Correct errno check on strtol call

According to errno man page:
   errno
       The value in errno is significant only when the return value of
       the call indicated an error (i.e., -1 from most system calls; -1
       or NULL from most library functions); a function that succeeds is
       allowed to change errno.  The value of errno is never set to zero
       by any system call or library function.

Hence do not assume errno to be zero at the end of a successful system
call, unless errno is set explicitly to zero before invoking the system
call.

Safe practice is to:
 - Either check the errno only on error case (that is, when return value
   does not indicate success), or
 - Set errno to zero before invoking the system call and checking it
   for errors after.

Resolves: LE-16338
Change-Id: Iaba413cd52a3059090f326780c1599ad67aa4b06
Signed-off-by: Anju Kunjumon <akunjumon@sierrawireless.com>

subject: Introduce "admin-connect" SMACK label
commitMessage:
Introduce "admin-connect" SMACK label

Service directory mediates connections between Legato daemons. It
passes client sockets to servers via socket CMSG mechanism. When
clients connect to serviceDirectory, this assigns client task
labels to SMACK64IPIN/IPOUT socket labels. When such a socket is
received by the server, it undergoes a SMACK security check: it
checks if SMACK64IPIN label can write to server label and it
checks if server label can write to SMACK64IPOUT label. If either
of clients/servers is labeled "admin", the other end would require
write permissions to "admin". This is undesirable since it could
theoretically replace any "admin" proces on disk, which violates
security.

Introduce an intermediary label "admin-connect". Promote
serviceDirectory to "admin" so that it could change SMACK labels
on passed sockets. Demote any "admin" labels on passed sockets to
"admin-connect" and add SMACK rules for "admin-connect". Remove
any existing write permissions to "admin".

Note that "admin-connect" label is reserved for sockets. For
security reasons, none of the processes should use this label.

Resolves: LE-15818
Change-Id: I09b9e7cff7192a67e4bf6bb5c935f940bbb43bab
Signed-off-by: Zoran Markovic <zmarkovic@sierrawireless.com>

Please confirm that removing this does not break and builds, particularly if MK_CONFIG_ATSERVER_LITE is not set to 'y'.

This MK_CONFIG_ATSERVER_LITE macro was used for two purposes:
(1). distinguish between atServer (the original one) and atProxy on MAP side.
(2). distinguish between MAP and MCU, as the latter doesn't support data mode previously.

For (1), there are many places in adef (such as at.adef and atIp.adef) and sdef files using this macro to do the correct binding which is still needed, as atSwi and atIp are shared by all platforms. Thus we cannot remove those macros there.

For (2), the purpose is gone as MCU is going to support data mode as well. Because both the MAP and MCU will support data mode, the macro here in this cdef file is inside atProxy itself for this purpose (2). Thus, shall be removed, otherwise, making no sense as MCU has to define this macro if not remove it here.
Instead of adding the explicit path here, can you add it to the interfaceSearch: section of the sdef?
I suggest renaming this to something like, pa_portService_SendDataModeStatus(), or something similar.

subject: Prevent invalid function parameters
commitMessage:
Prevent invalid function parameters

Test automation scripts found that le_atServer_Send* functions do not
prevent invalid parameters: when test programs provided NULL values to
these functions, the system would crash.

To resolve this issue, we need to follow the defensive programming
style: use assert() to check parameter values, so the system will crash
when programmers do not follow the API specification.

Resolves: LE-13938
Change-Id: Iadbb6a75907bf713d7783b21ce13b9c7db4fc3e5

subject: Load framework config before processing sdef
commitMessage:
Load framework config before processing sdef

In LE-16328 the location where interface search paths were added was
moved later in the sdef processing path to allow platform-specific
interfaces to be overridden in .sdef files.  However this had the
side-effect of including the framework configuration variables later in
processing as well, breaking .sdef files which depended on conditionals
on these configuration.

This change splits where interface search paths are added from where the
framework configuration is read and moves the framework configuration
back to its original location.

Resolves: LE-16371
Change-Id: Iff0f47f44534aef2b7850735f35ff08a224e99e5

subject: Invalid ATIP command format fix
commitMessage:
Invalid ATIP command format fix

Issue Description:
Legato can't detect the invalid format for ATIP comamnd.
Like AT+KHTTPCFG=3,"www.example.com (lost a quotation mark)

Root Cause:
When end of the AT command parsing, it won't handle the situations
about there have only one double quote.

Solution:
Legato will return error when end of the AT command parsing and
only have one double quote.

Resolves: LE-14956
Change-Id: Ib0aef5d2e5e9d458619e8328a8d4769912a672a0
Signed-off-by: CSU <csu@sierrawireless.com>
(cherry picked from commit a04eee9ed78c8f25b8716e6d75daa54885a15b3c)

You only handle the case when the string parameter is the last one, such as: AT+KHTTPCFG=3,"www.example.com

However, if it is not the last one, such as: AT+KHTTPCFG=3,"www.example.com,,,, can you still handle it?

Thanks for your review. 
In your case, this patch can handle, like:
AT+KCNXCFG=1,"GPRS","ip,,,
+CME ERROR: 3

But I found another case, like:
AT+KCNXCFG=1,"GPRS","ip","user,password"
OK
It should be +CME ERROR: 3 instead of OK.
So I update the patch.

subject: Invalid ATIP command format fix
commitMessage:
Invalid ATIP command format fix

Issue Description:
Legato can't detect the invalid format for ATIP comamnd.
Like AT+KHTTPCFG=3,"www.example.com (lost a quotation mark)

Root Cause:
When end of the AT command parsing, it won't handle the situations
about there have only one double quote.

Solution:
Legato will return error when end of the AT command parsing and
only have one double quote.

Resolves: LE-14956
Change-Id: If85263c352594b190e18923390415391a3e3f148
Signed-off-by: C.H. Su <csu@sierrawireless.com>

subject: Fix handling disconnect broadcast
commitMessage:
Fix handling disconnect broadcast

On some platforms disconnect notification will be broadcast for all
profiles by setting profile ID to -1.  In this case re-send the
notification to all known profile references instead of dropping it.

Resolves: LE-14206
Change-Id: Ieadefeb15f7d41033833b2dee602afeafef8b4f8

Klocwork [Critical NPD.FUNC.MUST #6687 @ hl7802]

> Pointer 'profilePtr' returned from call to function 'le_ref_GetValue' at line 296 may be NULL and will be dereferenced at line 298.
I think Klocwork is right this time: le_ref_GetValue() can return NULL.

Except it cannot at this point since if le_ref_NextNode() returns OK iterRef is guaranteed to be at a valid entry, and le_ref_GetValue() only returns NULL if the iterator is not on a valid value.  But this is a common problem with Klocwork -- it doesn't understand precondition/postcondition of functions, and I don't think there's a method of annotating the function to indicate this kind of information.  I'll add an ASSERT.

subject: Refactor le_atDefs to split out platform limits
commitMessage:
Refactor le_atDefs to split out platform limits

Refactor le_atDefs along the lines of the new guidance on creating
scaling APIs: Split potentially platform-specific definitions into a new
le_atLimits.api, and modify le_atDefs.api to refer to these definitions.

Since Legato system APIs are automatically added to the search path,
modify mkTools to add the new platformLimits directory to the end of the
interfaceSearch path.  This allows the default limits to be included
automatically, while still allowing a user to override these limits
manually.

Resolves: LE-16328
Change-Id: I78173363ec6cf9cf5d3731d9a0cb221d9d41b9d0

subject: Add ability to set config entries in adef & sdef files
commitMessage:
Add ability to set config entries in adef & sdef files

This change allows a default configuration for an app to be specifid in
the app definition file.  This configuration is also overridable in the
system's sdef file in case the system integrator wishes to use a different
default configuration than assumed by the app developer.

Resolves: LE-7673
Change-Id: I4b282c79780e21d102b4a10d25f8964f31c294d3

Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

> (3 comments)
 > 
 > The problem with this design is that once there's any kind of
 > config tree on target, new config section changes in .adef and
 > .sdef will be ignored.  

We're also running into the same issue with bundled files (at least if writable) -- once a bundled file has been placed on the target, if the contents are changed in the app it will not be updated on target, even if the target file has not been written.

I think the solution should instead be the upgrader should track if a file (or configuration setting) has been modified since the app was installed.  If no, the new version overwrites the old version.  If it has been modified do nothing.  Or maybe call app-provided upgrader util, according to a policy.

Regardless, I think we can provide this feature solely as a method for providing _initial_ configuration settings for now, and still have it useful.

Patch Set 2:

>  I think we can provide this feature solely as a method for providing _initial_ configuration settings for now, and still have it useful.

My concern with that is that it will cement the behaviour at that, which is not what we want long term.

subject: Add function to fetch free memory regions in memory pools
commitMessage:
Add function to fetch free memory regions in memory pools

Add a new function le_mdm_GetFreeLIst which will construct a list
of free memory regions within the pool space.  As this memory is
free, the list entries are constructed in-place, thus this rquires
no RAM.

Resolves: LE-15900
Change-Id: Id9ceae0984da2395ee72c8c9d41fbdea1116d2b4

subject: Fix linux compilation with RPC enabled
commitMessage:
Fix linux compilation with RPC enabled

Currently, unless LE_CONFIG_RTOS or LE_CONFIG_RPC_PROXY_LIBRARY is set,
RPC_PROXY_LOCAL_SERVICE will be unset. And there is some code that is
dependent on that flag being set to expose certain variables, but they
are still being accessed.

Now, added the RPC_PROXY_LOCAL_SERVICE flags around sections of the
code that utilize these variables that were being accessed.

Change-Id: Ibf350e9b70acaa669f182942ef89e68ecca8cd0e
Resolves: LE-15632
